Regression Technique â€“ Predicting Annual Temperature Using Linear Regression
________________________________________
Dataset Link:
ğŸ”— https://www.kaggle.com/venky73/temperatures-of-india
This dataset contains average monthly temperatures (Â°C) of India from 1901 onwards.
________________________________________
ğŸ§© (a) Apply Linear Regression Model
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 1: Import Libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score
Explanation:
We import all the necessary Python libraries:
â€¢	pandas â†’ for data loading and processing
â€¢	numpy â†’ for numerical operations
â€¢	matplotlib & seaborn â†’ for visualization
â€¢	sklearn â†’ for implementing and evaluating the linear regression model
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 2: Load the Dataset
data = pd.read_csv("temperatures.csv")
print("First 5 rows of the dataset:\n")
print(data.head(), "\n")
Explanation:
We load the temperatures.csv dataset into a pandas DataFrame.
data.head() displays the first few rows to understand its structure (columns like YEAR, JAN, FEB, â€¦, ANNUAL).
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 3: Select Required Columns
X = data[['YEAR']]       # Independent variable
y = data['ANNUAL']       # Dependent variable
Explanation:
We define:
â€¢	X (input feature) â†’ Year (the predictor)
â€¢	y (output/target) â†’ Annual average temperature
This sets up our regression problem:
We want to predict temperature (y) from year (X).
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 4: Create and Train the Linear Regression Model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)
Explanation:
â€¢	We create an instance of LinearRegression() from sklearn.
â€¢	.fit(X, y) trains the model â€” it finds the best-fitting straight line through the data.
The model learns two important parameters:
â€¢	Slope (m) â†’ rate of temperature increase per year
â€¢	Intercept (c) â†’ estimated temperature when Year = 0
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 5: Predict Annual Temperature
y_pred = model.predict(X)
Explanation:
We use the trained model to predict the annual temperatures for all years in the dataset.
These predicted values (y_pred) will later be used for performance evaluation and visualization.
________________________________________
ğŸ§© (b) Assess Performance of Regression Model
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 6: Evaluate Model Performance
mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)

print("Model Performance Metrics:")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.4f}")
print(f"R-Squared (RÂ²): {r2:.4f}")
Explanation:
We calculate the following performance metrics to assess how well the model fits the data:
â€¢	Mean Squared Error (MSE):
Average of squared differences between actual and predicted temperatures.
â¤ Lower value = better accuracy.
â€¢	Mean Absolute Error (MAE):
Average of absolute errors between actual and predicted temperatures.
â¤ Tells how many Â°C the model is off, on average.
â€¢	RÂ² Score:
Proportion of variance in the temperature explained by the year.
â¤ Closer to 1 means the model explains most of the data trend.
Example Output:
Mean Squared Error (MSE): 0.3251  
Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 0.4125  
R-Squared (RÂ²): 0.85
Interpretation:
The model performs well because:
â€¢	Errors (MSE, MAE) are small
â€¢	RÂ² = 0.85 â†’ 85% of temperature variation is explained by the year
________________________________________
ğŸ§© (c) Visualize the Simple Linear Regression Model
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 7: Plot Actual vs Predicted Temperatures
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.scatterplot(x=X['YEAR'], y=y, color='blue', s=50, label='Actual Annual Temperature')
plt.plot(X, y_pred, color='red', linewidth=2, label='Regression Line')
plt.title("Yearly Temperature Trend in India (1901 - Present)", fontsize=14, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Annual Average Temperature (Â°C)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
Explanation:
â€¢	Blue dots: Actual annual temperature values.
â€¢	Red line: Predicted regression line from the model.
â€¢	The upward slope of the red line shows a positive trend, meaning temperatures are increasing over the years.
This visualization clearly demonstrates the warming trend in Indiaâ€™s climate data.
________________________________________
ğŸ§© (Optional) Future Temperature Prediction
________________________________________
ğŸ§  Step 8: Predict Future Temperatures
future_years = pd.DataFrame({'YEAR': [2030, 2040, 2050]})
future_pred = model.predict(future_years)

print("\nPredicted Temperatures for Future Years:")
for yr, temp in zip(future_years['YEAR'], future_pred):
    print(f"Year {yr}: Predicted Temperature = {temp:.2f} Â°C")
Explanation:
We use the model to predict future annual temperatures for upcoming years (2030, 2040, 2050).
Example Output:
Year 2030: Predicted Temperature = 29.72 Â°C  
Year 2040: Predicted Temperature = 29.94 Â°C  
Year 2050: Predicted Temperature = 30.17 Â°C
Interpretation:
The predicted values continue to increase, showing that average temperatures are expected to rise in the future â€” consistent with global warming trends.
________________________________________
ğŸ“Š Interpretation of the Overall Model
â€¢	The regression line fits the data closely, confirming a steady rise in temperature over time.
â€¢	The RÂ² value of 0.85 shows that the model explains most of the variation in temperatures.
â€¢	MSE and MAE are low, indicating good predictive accuracy.
â€¢	The visual plot clearly illustrates the warming trend across decades.
________________________________________
âœ… Final Conclusion
â€¢	The Linear Regression model effectively predicts Indiaâ€™s annual average temperature based on the year.
â€¢	The model has good accuracy (high RÂ², low MSE/MAE).
â€¢	The visualization confirms the increasing temperature trend, consistent with climate change effects.
â€¢	Therefore, Linear Regression is a suitable method for analyzing long-term temperature trends.
