________________________________________
Q1. What is Linear Regression?
A: Linear Regression is a statistical method that models the relationship between a dependent variable (Y) and one or more independent variables (X) using a straight line.
________________________________________
Q2. What was the objective of your experiment?
A: To predict Indiaâ€™s annual average temperature based on the year using simple linear regression.
________________________________________
Q3. Which dataset did you use?
A: The dataset â€œTemperatures of Indiaâ€ from Kaggle, containing monthly and annual temperature data from 1901 onwards.
________________________________________
Q4. What are the independent and dependent variables in your model?
A:
â€¢	Independent Variable (X): Year
â€¢	Dependent Variable (Y): Annual Average Temperature
________________________________________
Q5. Which Python libraries did you use?
A:
pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, and sklearn.
________________________________________
Q6. What function is used to create a Linear Regression model in Python?
A: LinearRegression() from the sklearn.linear_model module.
________________________________________
Q7. How do you train the model?
A: By using the function model.fit(X, y) which fits the linear regression line to the data.
________________________________________
Q8. What is the formula of the Linear Regression line?
A:
[
Y = mX + c
]
where
â€¢	m = slope of the line
â€¢	c = intercept
________________________________________
Q9. What performance metrics did you use to evaluate the model?
A:
â€¢	Mean Squared Error (MSE)
â€¢	Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
â€¢	RÂ² Score
________________________________________
Q10. What does RÂ² Score indicate?
A: It indicates how well the model explains the variation in the data.
An RÂ² value of 0.85 means 85% of the variation in temperature is explained by the year.
________________________________________
